04388nam a22006615i 9780801469978DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20132013nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808014699787 a10.7591/97808014699782doi  a(DE-B1597)478457  a(OCoLC)979970030  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aHIS0100102bisacsh04a949.903/21 aGanev, Venelin I., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPreying on the State :bThe Transformation of Bulgaria after 1989 /cVenelin I. Ganev. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. The Dysfunctionality of Post-Communist State Structures -- t2. The Separation of Party and State as a Logistical Problem -- t3. Conversions of Power -- t4. Winners as State Breakers in Post-Communism -- t5. Weak-State Constitutionalism -- t6. The Shrewdness of the Tamed -- t7. Post-Communism as an Episode of State Transformation -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aImmediately after 1989, newly emerging polities in Eastern Europe had to contend with an overbearing and dominant legacy: the Soviet model of the state. At that time, the strength of the state looked like a massive obstacle to change; less than a decade later, the state's dominant characteristic was no longer its overweening powerfulness, but rather its utter decrepitude. Consequently, the role of the central state in managing economies, providing social services, and maintaining infrastructure came into question. Focusing on his native Bulgaria, Venelin I. Ganev explores in fine-grained detail the weakening of the central state in post-Soviet Eastern Europe.Ganev starts with the structural characteristics of the Soviet satellites, and in particular the forms of elite agency favored in the socialist party-state. As state socialism collapsed, Ganev demonstrates, its institutional legacy presented functionaries who had become accustomed to power with a matrix of opportunities and constraints. In order to maximize their advantage under such conditions, these elites did not need a robust state apparatus—in fact, all of the incentives under postsocialism pushed them to subvert the infrastructure of governance.Throughout Preying on the State, Ganev argues that the causes of state malfunctioning go much deeper than the policy preferences of "free marketeers" who deliberately dismantled the state. He systematically analyzes the multiple dimensions, implications, and significance of the institutional and social processes that transformed the organizational basis of effective governance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aSociology & Social Science. 4aSoviet & East European History. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Eastern.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080146997840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801469978423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780801469978.jpg  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK